rComments: Prof. Simion is one the best professors I've ever had. I was nervous because I didn't have much CS experience, but I absolutely loved the class. The course is difficult, but he is super organized and helpful in office hours so it is 100% possible to do really well in the class.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Lots of homework', 'Caring']

rComments: He changed teaching method to test the result for his own research and dont care about whether it is good for us or not.
It is just cumbersome that we have to do preps before the following week where we learn the same thing again.
Having an exam worth 61% and then failing most of us on it is not very helpful for first year students.

One of my favorite profs at UofT. Such a solid dude, he really knows how to deliver an informative lecture. Very good pace to the lectures, not too fast not too slow, while making challenging concepts seem "easy". He will be missed at the St. George campus !!

You will like Romania after taking csc369/367 with this man. Great courses with great assignments. Terrific lecture notes. You get the sense that it is permanent knowledge (unlike CSC309 which is ridiculously fickle). Highly recommended. Assignments were really interesting.

Professor Bogdan S. is one of favourite profs at U of T (along with Karen Reid). He legitimately cares about his students, and wants them to do well in the course. I took his Operating Systems course (CSC369) in Fall 2018 and I'm glad I did. It's a tough course, lots of material but you'll learn a lot. MUST start his assignments early!
teacherRatingTags: ['Accessible outside class', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Caring']

rComments: He is amazing, one of the best CS prof in Uoft

Really good professor overall. Technically strong, delivers good lectures, solves doubts with interest and creates challenging assignments. Lectures are peppered with jokes, puns as well as real world insight into whatever topic is being taught that day.

He is very good at lecturing, and tries to engage students in discussion (although he doesn't force anyone to participate). He covers a lot of material and the labs can be really time-consuming, but it is not at all an impossible class. The exams reflect what is covered in class and on the slides. Overall, I learned a lot in his class.

On the downside, his voice is a little monotone. On the flip side, he is such a caring prof. He legitimately wants you to do well, and his slides are great. Honestly I'd take a course with him over almost any other CS prof
Not a good prof. Only reads off the slides in lecture and expects you to know and understand things before you were ever taught them.

Pros:  Funny, smart, ... Fastest exam grading turnaround time I've ever seen (1 or 2 days?)  Highly active on class piazza forum.  Considerate of students' workloads.   Cons:  Difficult to ask many questions in office hours due to short/limited available time.  A little too snarky and praises a bit Linus Torvalds too much.  Be sharp to get respect.

Bogdan clearly cares a lot about his students -- he is available and willing to provide extra help if people need it. However his lectures are not very good. He mostly just reads from his slides which are confusing and not very clear, and doesn't make the material interesting. I would have enjoyed the course a lot more with a different prof.
Best lecturer in the department apart from the monotony of his voice
Excellent professor. Assignments are great learning experiences. Very helpful, and very thorough. Lecture material is always useful.

Lecture slides are great, gives good examples, and is great in office hours. He's approachable and you can tell he wants his students to do well. Yeah he has an accent but it's never given me a problem. Great with answering on the discussion board too.

He's really nice and helpful during office hours. I feel like he genuinely wants his students to learn the material. I like the worksheets he gives in class - they help clarify the points he's making and show me when I need to really read the readings.

He's a good instructor. I like him. He has an accent but he's pretty clear when he speaks. He is fairly easier than Reid (who also teaches this course). He's there for help if you need it. Lectures can get boring.
